[06:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'It\'s a starting point. The clips it makes need a human\'s taste and editing before they\'re good. But as a way to go from blank screen to a rough draft video in minutes, it\'s genuinely impressive. And that\'s'

[06:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'why 90,000 people starred it. Number three, and now the pattern gets undeniable. Headroom. 44,000 stars, almost all of them this month.'

[07:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Headroom does one thing beautifully. It compresses tool outputs, logs, files, and search results before they ever reach the model. Picture your AI agent about to read a giant log file.'

[07:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Headroom squeezes it first, keeping the meaning, dropping the noise, and cuts the tokens by 60 to 95%. With no change to your code. Every token you send costs money'

[07:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and fills up the model\'s limited memory. Headroom is a money-saving filter sitting in front of the brain. This is the context war in its purest form. Number two,'

[07:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Code Graph. 52,000 stars, 44,000 of them this month. One of the fastest climbs on the board. Here\'s the problem it kills.'

[07:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'When you ask a coding agent a question about your project, it often reads dozens of files just to orient itself. Slow and expensive. Code Graph builds a pre-indexed map of your entire code base ahead of time'

[08:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and keeps it in sync as you code. So, agents like Claude Code, CodeX Coder, and Gemini can answer questions straight from the map instead of scanning everything. The makers measured it.'

[08:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Around 16% cheaper and 58% fewer tool calls. Give the agent a map and it stops getting lost. And number one, the fastest rising repo on the entire trending page this month,'

[08:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Understand Anything by Ego Next. 65,000 stars and climbing faster than anything else here. It takes any code base'

[08:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and turns it into an interactive knowledge graph. A living map you can explore, search, and literally ask questions about. Drop in a scary unfamiliar project and'

[08:58] [scene:talk]
